00:29:19.130 --> 00:29:22.215
to folks who probably need it?

00:29:22.215 --> 00:29:23.590
TAZ BHATIA: That's
such a great--

00:29:23.590 --> 00:29:26.270
AUDIENCE: More than, maybe,
some of us, or some others.

00:29:26.270 --> 00:29:26.900
TAZ BHATIA: Yeah, definitely.

00:29:26.900 --> 00:29:28.400
I mean, I think the
obesity epidemic

00:29:28.400 --> 00:29:30.440
has happened for a number
of different reasons.

00:29:30.440 --> 00:29:33.120
Probably the number one
reason is, honestly,

00:29:33.120 --> 00:29:35.750
our food sourcing and the
production of our food.

00:29:35.750 --> 00:29:37.880
The more and more
we dig into obesity,

00:29:37.880 --> 00:29:39.830
we're understanding
that a lot of what

00:29:39.830 --> 00:29:42.710
was used over the last 30,
40 years between additives,

00:29:42.710 --> 00:29:45.080
and fillers, and preservatives,
and things like that

00:29:45.080 --> 00:29:47.570
have been hormone disruptors
and have contributed

00:29:47.570 --> 00:29:48.990
to that conversation.

00:29:48.990 --> 00:29:50.930
So when it comes
to obesity, again,

00:29:50.930 --> 00:29:54.530
if we can educate a
family on the right way

00:29:54.530 --> 00:29:56.230
to eat in a way that's not--

00:29:56.230 --> 00:29:59.660
everyone has a preconceived
notion that eating healthy

00:29:59.660 --> 00:30:00.680
is expensive.

00:30:00.680 --> 00:30:04.260
So if we can help families
learn to navigate that terrain

00:30:04.260 --> 00:30:06.365
so they understand how
to make healthy choices.

00:30:06.365 --> 00:30:08.240
And, again, it usually
starts with the woman.

00:30:08.240 --> 00:30:09.260
Because the woman's
doing the cooking,

00:30:09.260 --> 00:30:10.301
the shopping, the buying.

00:30:10.301 --> 00:30:13.580
So the more empowered you can
make the woman of the family,

00:30:13.580 --> 00:30:15.980
typically it'll go
out into the children

00:30:15.980 --> 00:30:18.170
and into the adult other
adults of the family

00:30:18.170 --> 00:30:20.480
to help with the obesity crisis.

00:30:20.480 --> 00:30:23.480
We just are also a culture
of over-consumption,

00:30:23.480 --> 00:30:24.410
quite honestly.

00:30:24.410 --> 00:30:27.290
You know we're eating way
more than we need to eat.

00:30:27.290 --> 00:30:30.170
And that goes to our children
and it goes to us as adults,

00:30:30.170 --> 00:30:30.920
as well.

00:30:30.920 --> 00:30:33.740
So helping people understand
what normal consumption is,

00:30:33.740 --> 00:30:34.970
I think is a big part of it.

00:30:34.970 --> 00:30:37.178
And that's where the whole
conversation on food waste

00:30:37.178 --> 00:30:38.000
also comes up.

00:30:38.000 --> 00:30:40.010
Because we waste
so much food, too.

00:30:40.010 --> 00:30:42.380
So the obesity
conversation, I know

00:30:42.380 --> 00:30:46.310
there's been a huge spotlight
with movement and activity.

00:30:46.310 --> 00:30:49.700
I'm going to push back on that
and say it's honestly 80% food

00:30:49.700 --> 00:30:51.505
and it's only 20% activity.

00:30:51.505 --> 00:30:52.880
And I think that's
where maybe we

00:30:52.880 --> 00:30:55.200
have the conversation
wrong to a certain extent.

00:30:55.200 --> 00:30:59.720
I do also think that technology
is an issue for obesity

00:30:59.720 --> 00:31:00.449
in the future.

00:31:00.449 --> 00:31:02.990
How are we going to take this
tool, this amazing tool that we

00:31:02.990 --> 00:31:06.050
have, of being connected to
anyone, anywhere in the world,

00:31:06.050 --> 00:31:08.400
and get information
at any given moment.

00:31:08.400 --> 00:31:11.030
But at the same time create
some boundaries and parameters

00:31:11.030 --> 00:31:12.950
so that people are
using it in a way that

00:31:12.950 --> 00:31:15.750
is productive and proactive
and not working against them?

00:31:15.750 --> 00:31:18.410
So the biggest thing I've
seen in pediatrics, which

00:31:18.410 --> 00:31:21.830
is another one of my
medical loves, so to speak,

00:31:21.830 --> 00:31:25.670
but is that children
don't have the boundaries

00:31:25.670 --> 00:31:27.200
to navigate technology.

00:31:27.200 --> 00:31:28.790
And adults don't
have the education

00:31:28.790 --> 00:31:30.830
to help them navigate
those boundaries.

00:31:30.830 --> 00:31:33.200
And, again, as much
as I know, I've

00:31:33.200 --> 00:31:35.150
struggled with my two children.

00:31:35.150 --> 00:31:37.110
And what's normal,
what's not normal, what's

00:31:37.110 --> 00:31:37.610
OK.

00:31:37.610 --> 00:31:40.340
So I think technology,
I think food, first.

00:31:40.340 --> 00:31:42.260
I think our food is
the biggest problem.

00:31:42.260 --> 00:31:44.750
I think looking at
technology and looking

00:31:44.750 --> 00:31:47.270
at how children are trapped
in rooms a lot of the times.

00:31:47.270 --> 00:31:48.590
They're not outside.

00:31:48.590 --> 00:31:51.380
I think the over scheduling
of families is an issue, too.

00:31:51.380 --> 00:31:53.810
I mean all of these
things are factors that

00:31:53.810 --> 00:31:55.970
play into obesity, for sure.

00:31:55.970 --> 00:31:59.660
And then when it comes to
different socioeconomic groups,

00:31:59.660 --> 00:32:03.050
helping them with
food deserts and areas

00:32:03.050 --> 00:32:04.790
that aren't getting
high-quality food.

00:32:04.790 --> 00:32:06.748
There's so many-- I could
talk forever on this,

00:32:06.748 --> 00:32:08.924
and I'll probably need to stop.

00:32:08.924 --> 00:32:10.340
But there's so
many great studies.

00:32:10.340 --> 00:32:13.730
Like if you give a young child--
any socioeconomic status--

00:32:13.730 --> 00:32:16.490
if you give them salads,
and healthy vegetables,

00:32:16.490 --> 00:32:19.230
and all that other stuff, they
will continue to choose that.

00:32:19.230 --> 00:32:22.610
But the minute you introduce
a high-salt high-fat food,

00:32:22.610 --> 00:32:24.680
their palate changes.

00:32:24.680 --> 00:32:26.270
And when they did
a study comparing

00:32:26.270 --> 00:32:28.880
lower socioeconomic
kids and their parents,

00:32:28.880 --> 00:32:31.250
and giving them food
choices, the kids actually

00:32:31.250 --> 00:32:32.840
chose the healthier foods.

00:32:32.840 --> 00:32:36.170
The parents had been so
acclimated to a certain taste

00:32:36.170 --> 00:32:38.780
that they chose
the junkier foods.

00:32:38.780 --> 00:32:41.990
So a lot of palate
training is happening.

00:32:41.990 --> 00:32:44.550
There's a lot that needs
to take place there.

00:32:44.550 --> 00:32:46.490
So I think it's
education, again.

00:32:46.490 --> 00:32:47.324
I think it's change.

00:32:47.324 --> 00:32:49.406
It's got to be change in
our industry and our food

00:32:49.406 --> 00:32:50.030
processing.

00:32:50.030 --> 00:32:52.910
And then creating environments
where children can thrive

00:32:52.910 --> 00:32:54.416
and adults can thrive as well.

00:32:54.416 --> 00:32:56.040
ARIEL ALTMAN: That's
